            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe still feels the chill of the polished marble counter against her fingertips from her first day at the boutique. She was 29, terrified, surrounded by handbags that cost more than her father\u2019s car. A woman asked her a question in French, and Sharon froze, the practiced phrases evaporating from her mind. The older manager smoothly intervened. That night, on the MUNI ride home, the shame was a physical weight. It wasn't defeat, but fuel. It ignited a fierce discipline in her to not just learn the job, but to master it.\n\n2.\nShe remembers the quiet click of the lock on the door of the empty apartment she once shared with her ex-husband. She was 41, and the future felt like a vast, unfurnished room. Standing on the sidewalk with two suitcases, watching the MUNI bus approach, she felt a terrifying clarity. There was no one to call for help; her survival was entirely her own again. That moment of profound solitude didn't break her; it forged her. It taught her that self-reliance was not a failure, but her most reliable luxury.\n\n3.\nThe day the painting was delivered felt more significant than any holiday. She was 45. For a full year, she had set aside part of her salary, forgoing dinners out and small indulgences for this one, stunning abstract piece. As she hung it on the wall of her rental, the vibrant canvas filled the space with a life that was purely hers. It was the first beautiful thing she had ever bought for no practical reason, a quiet declaration that her hard work could create not just stability, but also joy.\n\n4.\nShe can still picture the woman's hands\u2014manicured, weighted with jewels\u2014as she caressed a leather satchel. \"It's a gift for my daughter,\" she'd said dismissively, \"She's just starting out.\" Sharon saw past the casual wealth to the core emotion: a mother's hope. She spent an hour with her, not selling a bag, but affirming the woman's choice. Later, seeing the five-figure sale on her report was less important than the realization that her true talent was deciphering the quiet anxieties of the city's most powerful people.\n\n5.\nOne morning last year, rattling along on the 7 Haight bus, she saw a young woman get on, her face lit with pride. She was wearing a vintage coat, beautifully made but clearly not new. It fit her perfectly. In that girl, Sharon saw her younger self, dreaming of quality she couldn\u2019t afford. The image sparked. It wasn't about selling new things, but about honoring beautiful objects that last. In that instant on a public bus, the abstract ambition for \"something more\" finally took shape: a shop for second chances."
